Great question.

What you can do is use the score as the `key`, and use a list of id&#39;s at the `value`.

Consider the following.

```java
Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; parse(String string) {
    Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; map = new TreeMap&lt;&gt;();
    String[] strings = string.split(&quot; &quot;);
    int id, score;
    for (int index = 0; index &lt; strings.length; index += 2) {
        id = Integer.parseInt(strings[index]);
        score = Integer.parseInt(strings[index + 1]);
        if (map.containsKey(score)) map.get(score).add(id);
        else map.put(score, new ArrayList(Arrays.asList(id)));
    }
    return map;
}
```

If we parsed a value of `&quot;1 456 2 100 3 600 1 400&quot;`, we get the following.

```none
{100=[2], 400=[1], 456=[1], 600=[3]}
```

And, as demonstration, if parsed a value of `&quot;1 456 2 100 3 600 1 400 5 456 6 600&quot;`, we would get this.

```none
{100=[2], 400=[1], 456=[1, 5], 600=[3, 6]}
```

Then, for access, you can implement a method similar to the following.

```java
/** @return null if not found */
List&lt;Integer&gt; scores(int id, Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; map) {
    List&lt;Integer&gt; scores = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    for (Map.Entry&lt;Integer, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; entry : map.entrySet()) {
        if (entry.getValue().contains(id))
            scores.add(entry.getKey());
    }
    if (scores.isEmpty()) scores = null;
    return scores;
}
```

Output for `scores(1, parse(&quot;1 456 2 100 3 600 1 400&quot;))` is the following.

```none
[400, 456]
